Alexa+
------

From The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/news/619755/amazon-alexa-ai-upgra=
de-artificial-intelligence-smart-assistant ) :

Amazon is finally launching the long-awaited generative AI version of Alexa=
 =E2=80=94 Alexa Plus =E2=80=94 that, if all goes well, will take away much=
 of the friction that comes with talking to a speaker to control your smart=
 home or getting info on the fly. Some of the new abilities coming to Alexa=
 Plus include the ability to do things for you =E2=80=94 you=E2=80=99ll be =
able to ask it to order groceries for you or send event invites to your fri=
ends. Amazon says it will also be able to memorize personal details like yo=
ur diet and movie preferences.

Alexa Plus is $19.99 per month on its own or free for Amazon Prime members =
=E2=80=94 a better deal, considering Prime costs just $14.99 per month or $=
139 per year. That comes with access to the Alexa website, where the compan=
y said you can do =E2=80=9Clongform work.=E2=80=9D Amazon also said it crea=
ted a new Alexa app to go with the new assistant. Alexa Plus will work on =
=E2=80=9Calmost every=E2=80=9D Alexa device released so far, starting with =
the Echo Show 8, 10, 15, and 21. The new system will be free for anyone in =
early access, which will start rolling out next month.

The event announcing Alexa+ was a week ago, and, to be honest, I'm almost n=
ot sure if I should even write about it. First off, there was no video of t=
he event; it's 2025 and the live blog is back ( https://www.theverge.com/ne=
ws/618261/amazon-alexa-event-live-blog-2025 ) ! Moreover, there was no vide=
o put up after the event either; Amazon does have a couple of promo videos:

( https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/YYbAJ2nh25M?si=3DxfOOPJF8sUcy0sVP =
)
( https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/DeHX99wycug?si=3DHWCHLvFagCVQB0rK =
)

Is this pure vaporware?

Fortunately, Jennifer Tuohy at The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/news/62=
1008/hands-on-with-alexa-plus-smart-home-echo-show-21 ) did come out with a=
 hands-on report a couple of days after the event, so apparently Alexa+ doe=
s in fact exist in a state that is accessible by non-Amazon employees. From=
 her report:

I was also able to talk to the assistant myself and try out its new ability=
 to follow multiple commands at once without needing to repeat the wake wor=
d, Alexa. I asked it to dim the lights and adjust the thermostat to =E2=80=
=9Cmake it a little warmer.=E2=80=9D The thermostat adjusted while the ligh=
ts dimmed, and Alexa said, =E2=80=9CI dimmed the lights in the living room =
and increased the temperature by two degrees; is there anything else you ne=
ed?=E2=80=9D I then said, =E2=80=9CCan you vacuum the floor?=E2=80=9D It re=
plied, =E2=80=9COkay,=E2=80=9D and the Roomba started a job.

Another new feature I tried was the ability to set up a smart home routine =
just by using voice. I told Alexa I=E2=80=99d been having trouble waking up=
 recently, and after some back-and-forth, it created a =E2=80=9CGood Mornin=
g=E2=80=9D routine that set an alarm to wake me up to Taylor Swift=E2=80=99=
s =E2=80=9CShake It Off=E2=80=9D and adjust the smart lights in my room.

That=E2=80=99s a fairly simple one because there weren=E2=80=99t a lot of d=
evices connected to the Show. But Amazon says that, courtesy of its knowled=
ge of hundreds of smart home APIs, Alexa is capable of creating more comple=
x routines through voice. This should make it easier for people to do more =
with their connected devices and not have to spend time programming an app.

This last paragraph gets at Amazon =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Apple and Google's =
=E2=80=94 potential peril and possibilities.

