I also think that Amazon got two big things right with Alexa, particularly =
as it expanded its "Skills", i.e. integrations with services and devices, e=
specially those related to home automation.

* First, Alexa was always very fast and, in my experience, very good at und=
erstanding what you said to it; this was a big distinguishing factor from S=
iri in particular, although Google quickly rivaled Alexa.
* Second, Amazon didn't attempt to do any fancy fuzzy matching when it came=
 to triggering "Skills"; if you wanted to use a device or service, you had =
to say the words exactly right.

This second point may seem counterintuitive, but I think it was a very smar=
t product choice given Alexa's capabilities. Instead of wowing users half o=
f the time and frustrating them the other half, with no clear feedback abou=
t why a particular command worked or didn't work, Alexa put the burden on t=
he user; again, speaking anecdotally, I would blame myself when a voice com=
mand didn't work, because I didn't say the right words. Alexa, for its part=
, understood what I said and told me whether it was successful or not, whic=
h allowed me to improve. Siri, to again take the counterexample, would try =
and be "smart" which actually made it much more frustrating.

I'm sure you can see where I'm going with this: the promise of LLMs is that=
 not only can you carry on a conversation with them about, well, anything, =
you should, at least in theory, be able to do the fuzzy matching that just =
wasn't possible previously. That's exactly what Tuohy was describing in the=
 excerpt above.

Amazon =E2=80=94 and Apple's =E2=80=94 Mistake
------------------------------

This also gets at why Amazon's announcement of Alexa+ makes me nervous: it =
feels way too ambitious. Alexa+ isn't just going to turn on your lights, it=
's also going to order you concert tickets and make a reservation at your f=
avorite restaurant and plan a vacation and call the babysitter; Alexa+ will=
 have memory and will learn and the list goes on-and-on, which is to say th=
at what Amazon is promising is substantially more advanced than basically a=
ny AI product on the market. It will certainly be impressive if the company=
 pulls all of this off, but it seems just as likely that it will suffer the=
 fate of Siri in the home automation wars of old: it will work amazingly so=
me of the time, and just fail the rest of the time, and that experience wil=
l be extremely frustrating for users.

What I would have preferred to see is exactly what Amazon smartly avoided i=
n the first go-around with voice assistants: natural language interaction a=
nd fuzzy matching for controlling "Skills", and even then, I wouldn't have =
started with all of them, just the home automation ones. Sure, that sounds =
boring and would make for a less exciting keynote =E2=80=94 not that anyone=
 actually saw it =E2=80=94 but it would have had a higher probability of wo=
rking all of the time, which would have built user trust for an actual legi=
timate use case that already exists, increasing their willingness in the fu=
ture to try the more advanced capabilities that would finally realize the d=
ream of Alexa as operating system for the home ( https://stratechery.com/20=
17/amazons-operating-system/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN=
0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVja=
GVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50=
Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDE3L2FtYXpvbnMtb3BlcmF0aW5=
nLXN5c3RlbS8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTc0Mzc3MzA3OCwiaWF0IjoxNzQxMTgxMDc4LCJpc3MiOiJodH=
RwczovL2FwcC5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY=
2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJz=
ZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.UIVbpDt2U0XdPKQBeudMHcSk=
tRZQVqe-CeQcap8ByKIQ1bxJd_Tf48De_zLgM5mA-Bers4bdGy3G2QqaMkUhqhY9TNMWtRyp5F-=
oxsBeKSfYHucAJpRHDLlkOJ1VqMpVTvhm_9G3JJJMZDePCHl_JlwJ64h1FpVJKPOFv7vR8oNPJ-=
B8AJFOxsgDLxlYwZD46XXspn9WpGDxGCZ23aBDAzOPhueIUF6zvDgYauh8auDA2Atz7PfSJ1hyx=
M7-Hvn2cJ7wTH_v02OF7e3dXB_YjmDYaBaetCuRppfeZ1v_vfCCqRwkwJ37IxakusnM4CMBehgo=
q3-RV4gyD0PN6fM8dA ).

I think that Apple is making the same mistake with Siri, by the way. Mark G=
urman reported in Bloomberg this week ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/arti=
cles/2025-02-14/apple-s-long-promised-ai-overhaul-for-siri-runs-into-bugs-p=
ossible-delays ) :

Apple Inc.=E2=80=99s long-promised overhaul for the Siri digital assistant =
is facing engineering problems and software bugs, threatening to postpone o=
r limit its release, according to people with knowledge of the matter. The =
company first unveiled plans for a new AI-infused Siri at its developers co=
nference last June and has even advertised some of the features to customer=
s. But Apple is still racing to finish the software, said the people, who a=
sked not to be identified because the situation is private. Some features, =
originally planned for April, may have to be postponed until May or later, =
they said.

The Siri makeover is a centerpiece of the Apple Intelligence platform, the =
company=E2=80=99s effort to catch up in AI and spur iPhone upgrades. Even b=
efore the Siri snags, Apple Intelligence has had a bumpy rollout. The softw=
are has been released in stages since an October debut, and some features =
=E2=80=94 such as news summaries =E2=80=94 have drawn criticism for glitche=
s. Getting Siri right is especially crucial for Apple, which first introduc=
ed the digital assistant in 2011 as a groundbreaking interface. After falli=
ng behind competitors, the technology has come to represent the company=E2=
=80=99s shortcomings in artificial intelligence.

New Siri, like Alexa+, promised to be much more than simply a voice assista=
nt that was easier to use: it is going to track flights and give restaurant=
 recommendations and make reservations and check your calendar and, well, a=
 lot of the same stuff that Amazon is promising. And here we are, nine mont=
hs on, and New Siri hasn't really launched, and is on the verge of being de=
layed.

Google, notably, is being smarter about the space; Gemini is an option for =
Google Assistant, but it's buried in options, and the company is honest tha=
t it doesn't work for a lot of use cases that Google Assistant currently ha=
ndles (and which Gemini falls back on). Of course you can fail in the other=
 direction, and never actually ship anything, but people use these devices =
to actually turn lights on and open curtains, and they need to be rock soli=
d at nailing the basics before they are pushed to the public.

Again, maybe new Siri will be on time, or only slightly delayed, and will b=
e awesome, and maybe Alexa+ is going to do everything Amazon demoed without=
 frustrating failures. I will absolutely tip my hat to each of them if they=
 pull it off.

If the real-world implementations are janky, though, I think the lesson is =
that big companies have an interesting failure case when it comes to new te=
chnologies: precisely because they have a toxic combination of too many res=
ources and too many internal incentives to show worth and self-imposed pres=
sure to "be innovative", they end up trying to do too much and create a pro=
duct that demos well and isn't actually useful.

This is where the new iPad comes in: that tweet may sting, but it shouldn't=
. The fact of the matter is that the iPad is a rock-solid device, and it's =
perfectly fine to ship a new one with a faster chip and call it a day. This=
 is how Apple rolls ( https://daringfireball.net/2010/05/this_is_how_apple_=
rolls ). After all, that iPad runs all of the apps that ran on the old iPad=
, just a bit faster. From a consumer perspective that may not be exciting, =
but "it just works" remains a differentiator.

And that, by extension, is why Amazon and Apple don't need to be in a rush:=
 both Alexa and Siri have a decade-plus head start in terms of integrations=
 with a host of devices and services. Alexa+ and New Siri don't need to hav=
e capabilities that exceed what even the frontier AI labs have yet to ship;=
 simply being better voice assistants for their existing ecosystems will ma=
ke them more useful (and, I should note, is a heavy lift in-and-of-itself; =
faithfully replicating existing functionally is a hard problem). That's the=
 power of being an ecosystem provider, and I suspect both companies should =
have a little bit more confidence in their relative advantage, and be a lit=
tle more conservative about their ambitions.

